//@ exit: 101

// `as` out of `any` is a CHECKED cast: the box carries the concrete type's tag, the
// cast compares it against the target's, and a mismatch TRAPS (exit 101) instead of
// reinterpreting the payload bytes at the wrong type.
//
// Before the check, `a as i64` on a box holding a `str` read the string's pointer word
// as an integer -- silently, for every type, which is the general form of the opaque
// forge pinned in records/opaque_no_any_laundering.neon. The checker is right to accept
// the cast -- `any` can hold anything, so the assertion could be true -- but an
// assertion that is never discharged is a reinterpret cast wearing a checked cast's
// name. It is discharged at run time, the one place the box's real type is known.
//
// The matching direction stays free: the round trip through `any` here recovers the
// value it erased, same as list_literal_erased_into_any_recovered.neon does for the
// container shape. "before" pins that the program really ran up to the bad cast.

use std::io;

fn main() {
    // Honest recovery: the tag matches, the value comes back.
    let a: any = 42;
    io::println(to_string(a as! i64));

    io::println("before");

    // Mismatch: the box holds a str, the cast claims i64. Traps here.
    let b: any = "hi";
    io::println(to_string(b as! i64));

    io::println("unreachable");
}
